\begin{definition}[Low-equivalence]
Two values, each consisting of a pair of values with labels ${l}, {l}'$ such that $ {l}' \not\flows{l}$, are equivalent according to the equivalence relation $=_L$  if they agree on the low values. Specifically, 
\begin{equation*}
\inferrule{(\Gamma \vdash e_j : (\Lvalue\ {l}'\ \tau'_i, \Lvalue\ {l}\ \tau_i))_{j=1,2} \\ (e_j\longrightarrow^* v_j)_{j=1,2}\\ \pi_2\ v_1 = \pi_2\ v_2\\ l \flows L\\ L\not\flows l}
{e_1 =_L e_2}
\end{equation*}
\end{definition}

The low-equivalence expresses the observing power of an attacker; an attacker may distinguish  values labeled with at most $L$.

For example, $(\Lv\ \lH\ 8,\Lv\ \lL\ 2) =_\lL (\Lv\ \lH\ 9,\Lv\ \lL\ 2)$, but 
$(\Lv\ \lH\ 8,\Lv\ \lL\ 2) \not =_{\lL} (\Lv\ \lH\ 8,\Lv\ \lL\ 3)$.
Similarly, if we extend the lattice with element $\lM : \lL\flows \lM \flows \lH$, 
$(\Lv\ \lH\ 8,\Lv\ \lL\ 2) =_\lL (\Lv\ \lM\ 9,\Lv\ \lL\ 2)$.


\begin{definition}[Low-view]
Two labeled values (each consisting of a pair of labeled values), are equivalent according to the equivalence relation $\approx_L$ if they are not observable, i.e., $L$ is lower than the labels of both values, or the pairs are low-equivalent.
\begin{equation*}
\inferrule{(\Gamma \vdash e_j : (\Lvalue\ l_j\ e_j'))_{j=1,2}\\ (l_1 \not\flows L \land l_2 \not\flows L)\lor (e_1'=_L e_2')}
          {e_1 \approx_L e_2}
\end{equation*}
\end{definition}

The low-view simply states that an attacker, who may observe values with label at most $L$, cannot distinguish two labeled values if they are either 1) both labeled above $L$, or 2) the values are low-equivalent.

For example, $\Lv\ \lM\ (\Lv\ \lH\ 8,\Lv\ \lL\ 2) \approx_{\lL} \Lv\ \lH\ (\Lv\ \lH\ 8,\Lv\ \lL\ 3)$, even though the labeled pairs are not low-equivalent.
Similarly, $\Lv\ \lM\ (\Lv\ \lH\ 8,\Lv\ \lL\ 2) \approx_\lM \Lv\ \lL\ (\Lv\ \lH\ 9,\Lv\ \lL\ 2)$, but
$\Lv\ \lL\ (\Lv\ \lH\ 8,\Lv\ \lL\ 2) \not =_{\lL} \Lv\ \lL\ (\Lv\ \lH\ 8,\Lv\ \lL\ 3)$.



\begin{theorem}[Non-interference]
Given labels ${l}, {l}'$ such that $ {l}' \not\flows{l}$,
a computation $e$ where $\Gamma \vdash e : (\Lvalue\ {l}'\ \tau'_i, \Lvalue\ {l}\ \tau_i) \rightarrow (\Lvalue\ {l}'\ \tau'_o, \Lvalue\ {l}\ \tau_o)$ in environment $\store$, such that $\store(\lbl)\flows l_i \flows \store(\clr)$ for $l_i = \{l,l'\}$,
and an attacker with clearance $L$ such that ${l} \flows L$ and ${l}' \not\flows L$,
\begin{align*}
\forall e_1 e_2.&(\Gamma \vdash e_j : (\Lvalue\ \ell'\ \tau'_i,\Lvalue\ \ell\ \tau_i))_{j=1,2}\\
&\land e_1 =_L e_2\\ 
&\land \langle \store, \close\ (e\ e_1)\rangle \longrightarrow^* \langle \store^\prime, v_1\rangle\\
&\land \langle \store, \close\ (e\ e_2)\rangle \longrightarrow^* \langle \store^\prime, v_2\rangle\\
&\Rightarrow v_1 \approx_{L} v_2.
\end{align*}
\end{theorem}

In other words, given two low-equivalent inputs, each consisting of a pair of values with a public and secret labels, the result of the well-behaved computation as observed by the attacker (at label level up to $L$) is indistinguishable.





















